    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "15.2.1 Analysis of GAN loss function"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b002",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 2,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "If we divide the two sums in the first line of equation 15.5 by the numbers I, J of real and generated samples, then the loss function can be written in terms of expectations:"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b003",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 3,
    "type": "equation",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "\\begin{aligned}L[\\phi]\\quad&=\\;-\\frac{1}{J}\\sum_{j=1}^{I}\\left(\\log\\left[1-\\mathrm{sig}[\\mathbf{f}[\\mathbf{x}_{j}^{*},\\phi]]\\right]\\right)-\\frac{1}{I}\\sum_{i=1}^{I}\\left(\\log\\left[\\mathrm{sig}[\\mathbf{f}[\\mathbf{x}_{i},\\phi]]\\right]\\right)\\\\&\\approx\\;-\\mathbb{E}_{\\mathbf{x}^{*}}\\left[\\log\\left[1-\\mathrm{sig}[\\mathbf{f}[\\mathbf{x}^{*},\\phi]]\\right]\\right]-\\mathbb{E}_{\\mathbf{x}}\\left[\\log\\left[\\mathrm{sig}[\\mathbf{f}[\\mathbf{x},\\phi]]\\right]\\right]\\\\&=\\;-\\int Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})\\log\\left[1-\\mathrm{sig}[\\mathbf{f}[\\mathbf{x}^{*},\\phi]]\\right]d\\mathbf{x}^{*}-\\int Pr(\\mathbf{x})\\log\\left[\\mathrm{sig}[\\mathbf{f}[\\mathbf{x},\\phi]]\\right]d\\mathbf{x},\\end{aligned}\n\\tag{15.6}"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b004",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 4,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "where $Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})$ is the probability distribution over the generated samples, and $Pr(\\mathbf{x})$ is the true probability distribution over the real examples."
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b005",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 5,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "When $I = J$, the optimal discriminator for an example $\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}$ of unknown origin is:"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b006",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 6,
    "type": "equation",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "\\begin{aligned}\nPr(\\mathrm{real}|\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}})=\\underset{}{\\mathrm{sig}\\left[\\mathrm{f}[\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}},\\phi]\\right]}=\\frac{Pr(\\bar{\\mathbf{x}}|\\mathrm{real})}{Pr(\\tilde{\\mathbf{x}}|g e n e r a t e d)+Pr(\\bar{\\mathbf{x}}|\\mathrm{real})}=\\frac{Pr(\\mathbf{x})}{Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})+Pr(\\bar{\\mathbf{x}})},\n\\end{aligned}\n\\tag{15.7}"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b007",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 7,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "where on the right hand side, we evaluate $\\tilde{x}$ against the generated distribution $Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})$ and the real distribution $Pr(x)$ . Substituting into equation 15.6, we get:"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b008",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 8,
    "type": "equation",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "\\begin{aligned}L[\\phi]\\;=\\;&-\\int Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})\\log\\Big[1-\\mathrm{sig}[\\mathbf{f}[\\mathbf{x}^{*},\\phi]]\\Big]d\\mathbf{x}^{*}-\\int Pr(\\mathbf{x})\\log\\Big[\\mathrm{sig}[\\mathbf{f}[\\mathbf{x},\\phi]]\\Big]d\\mathbf{x}\\\\=\\;&-\\int Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})\\log\\Bigg[1-\\frac{Pr(\\mathbf{x})}{Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})+Pr(\\mathbf{x})}\\Bigg]d\\mathbf{x}^{*}-\\int Pr(\\mathbf{x})\\log\\Bigg[\\frac{Pr(\\mathbf{x})}{Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})+Pr(\\mathbf{x})}\\Bigg]d\\mathbf{x}\\\\=\\;&-\\int Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})\\log\\Bigg[\\frac{Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})}{Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})+Pr(\\mathbf{x})}\\Bigg]d\\mathbf{x}^{*}-\\int Pr(\\mathbf{x})\\log\\Bigg[\\frac{Pr(\\mathbf{x})}{Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})+Pr(\\mathbf{x})}\\Bigg]d\\mathbf{x}.\\end{aligned}\n\\tag{15.7}"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b009",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 9,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "Problems 15.1–15.2"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b010",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 10,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "Disregarding additive and multiplicative constants, this is the Jensen-Shannon divergence between the synthesized distribution $Pr(x^{*})$ and the true distribution $Pr(x)$ :"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b011",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 11,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "Appendix C.5.2 Jensen-Shannon divergence"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b012",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 12,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "divergence"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b013",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 13,
    "type": "equation",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "\\begin{aligned}D_{JS}\\Big[Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})\\mid\\mid Pr(\\mathbf{x})&\\Big]\\\\&=\\frac{1}{2}D_{KL}\\left[\\left|\\frac{Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})+Pr(\\mathbf{x})}{2}\\right|+\\frac{1}{2}D_{KL}\\left[Pr(\\mathbf{x})\\mid\\left|\\frac{Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})+Pr(\\mathbf{x})}{2}\\right.\\right]\\right.\\\\&=\\frac{1}{\\circ}\\int Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})\\log\\left[\\underbrace{\\frac{2Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})}{Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})+Pr(\\mathbf{x})}}\\right]d\\mathbf{x}^{*}+\\frac{1}{\\circ}\\int Pr(\\mathbf{x})\\log\\left[\\underbrace{\\frac{2Pr(\\mathbf{x})}{Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})+Pr(\\mathbf{x})}}\\right]d\\mathbf{x}.\\end{aligned}\n\\tag{15.9}"
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b014",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 14,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "where $D_{KL}[\\bullet||\\bullet]$ is the Kullback-Leibler divergence."
  },
  {
    "id": "page_0282-b015",
    "page_key": 282,
    "order": 15,
    "type": "paragraph",
    "source": "deepseek+paddle",
    "confidence": "high",
    "text": "The first term indicates the distance will be small if, wherever the sample density $Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*})$ is high, the mixture $(Pr(\\mathbf{x}^{*}) + Pr(\\mathbf{x}))/2$ has high probability. In other words, it penalizes regions with samples $x^{*}$ but no real "
  }
]
